== Common Mistakes


#mistake-box(
  title: "Mistake #1: The Toothless Law",
  fix: [Show enforcement. Someone else has been punished. Getting caught would mean concrete, serious consequences. In #emph[Serpent & Dove], the law against witchcraft has real teeth because we see other witches burned. Lou doesn't just risk disapproval; she risks being set on fire by the man she's falling for. That's a law with consequences, and it's why the forbidden love in that story actually feels forbidden.],
)[
  There's a law against their relationship, but nobody enforces it. They're "forbidden" but face no real consequences. Forbidden love only matters if the forbidding has teeth.
]


#mistake-box(
  title: "Mistake #2: The Easily Escaped Arrangement",
  fix: [Make the arrangement matter. Breaking it means war, family ruin, or personal destruction. And make the arranged partner human, maybe even decent. The hardest choices aren't between good and evil. They're between two things that both have legitimate claims on your character's loyalty. Make the choice genuinely hard.],
)[
  One character is in an arranged marriage, but they can simply refuse, or the other betrothed is cartoonishly evil so breaking the arrangement is obviously right. Arranged marriage tension requires the arrangement to be genuinely binding. If the arranged partner is a moustache-twirling villain, there's no real dilemma. The reader knows our protagonist should leave, and the tension evaporates.
]


#mistake-box(
  title: "Mistake #3: The Vague or Vanishing Politics",
  fix: [Be specific about who wants what and why both sides can't have it. Ground the conflict in concrete goals and consequences. Then keep the pressure on. Politics should intensify during the romance, not pause. The war doesn't stop because they're falling in love. The betrothal doesn't dissolve because they've had a meaningful conversation. The law doesn't look the other way because the reader wants them to be happy. If anything, the deeper they fall, the more dangerous their situation becomes.],
)[
  There's political conflict, but it's unclear what anyone wants, what the stakes are, or why it matters. Or: serious political conflicts somehow stop mattering when the romance heats up. External pressure disappears when it's inconvenient. If readers don't understand the political situation, they can't feel the pressure on the relationship. And if that pressure lifts the moment the leads start falling for each other, the stakes feel fake. Readers need to believe the world would genuinely punish these characters if they're caught. #strong[Quick check: Does your story fall into any of these traps?] | Mistake | Does It Apply? | How You'll Fix It | |---------|---------------|-------------------| | Toothless law (forbidden but no real consequences) | | | | Easily escaped arrangement (obvious that they should leave) | | | | Vague/vanishing politics (unclear stakes or pressure disappears) | | |
]


